# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: arthur-s-pass-national-park
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/1080-usage-in-new-zealand] New Zealand is the largest user of 1080 poison, using about 80% of the world's supply.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/1080-usage-in-new-zealand] Biodegradable 1080 poison is the only poison currently registered for use on mainland New Zealand as suitable for aerial targeting of the common brushtail possum; a major conservation and agricultural pest.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/1080-usage-in-new-zealand] New Zealand has used 1080 for pest control since the late 1950s; it imports sodium fluoroacetate in raw form from the United States of America.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/1080-usage-in-new-zealand] New Zealand is unusual in that it has no naturally occurring extant terrestrial mammal, except for two species of bat.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/1080-usage-in-new-zealand] Similarly, no confirmed fossils of terrestrial mammals have been found in New Zealand from the 85 million years since the landmass split away from Gondwana (except for the St Bathans mammal which is of unclear lineage).
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/1080-usage-in-new-zealand] As such, New Zealand’s fauna and flora evolved in the absence of mammals and generally didn’t develop the evolutionary strategies needed to avoid predation by mammals.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/1080-usage-in-new-zealand] When human activity accidentally or deliberately introduced numerous species of invasive mammalian predators to New Zealand (most notably including rats, brush-tailed possums, cats and mustelids) many of New Zealand’s native species were unable to respond and were preyed upon.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/1080-usage-in-new-zealand] Because of this, the introduction of mammalian predators is strongly linked to the decline of New Zealand’s fauna and flora, having a disastrous effect on the populations of many iconic species including kiwi, tuatara and giant wētā.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/1080-usage-in-new-zealand] Because of the continuing impacts of mammalian predators in New Zealand, there is a strong need to utilise a range of specialised predator control tactics to protect New Zealand’s species, including the usage of 1080.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/1080-usage-in-new-zealand] The largest users of 1080 in New Zealand are the Animal Health Board and the Department of Conservation (DOC).
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/1080-usage-in-new-zealand] It is also used on a smaller scale for pest control by Regional Councils and private landowners.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/1080-usage-in-new-zealand] The first trials were carried out in New Zealand in 1954, and by 1957 its use had become widespread.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/1080-usage-in-new-zealand] 1080 baits are used through ground-based and aerial application.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/1080-usage-in-new-zealand] 1080 is considered to be suitable for use as a mammalian pest control in New Zealand because the country has only two native land mammals (bats).
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/1080-usage-in-new-zealand] 1080 is commonly used in Western Australia to kill feral carnivores, as the compound is naturally occurring in Western Australian flora and the native herbivores and their native predators are immune.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/1080-usage-in-new-zealand] When correctly applied, 1080 is very effective at controlling conservation pests.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/1080-usage-in-new-zealand] One aerial application can kill 98% of possums and more than 90% of rats in the targeted area.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/1080-usage-in-new-zealand] These successful knock-down rates provide vulnerable native birds with a crucial breeding window to raise chicks through to fledging, increasing their survival rate.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/1080-usage-in-new-zealand] The DOC uses aerially applied 1080 poison across about 440,000 ha of conservation land each year.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/1080-usage-in-new-zealand] This equates to 5% of the total conservation estate.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/1080-usage-in-new-zealand] DOC's pest control programme is governed by *residual trap catch* rates, the percentage of nights in which a trap catches a pest.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/1080-usage-in-new-zealand] Targets are usually set to less than 5%, though rates below 2% can be achieved by 1080.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/1080-usage-in-new-zealand] In New Zealand, the common brushtail possum was the main vector for the spread of bovine tuberculosis—a highly contagious disease affecting farmed cattle and deer.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/1080-usage-in-new-zealand] The disease was endemic in possums across about 38% of New Zealand (known as 'vector risk areas') but industry sources acknowledge the incidence of bovine TB fell to less than 0.05% in the areas where it is monitored.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/1080-usage-in-new-zealand] The organisation responsible for managing bovine TB in New Zealand, the Animal Health Board, uses 1080 poison as one of a range of pesticides to kill possums and control the spread of disease to both livestock and unaffected areas of the country.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/1080-usage-in-new-zealand] Aerial application of 1080 poison is only used in places where ground control methods are impractical or unable to reduce possum numbers to a low enough level to break the disease cycle.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/1080-usage-in-new-zealand] In 2011, this was less than 10% of the total area receiving possum control.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/1080-usage-in-new-zealand] Both aerial and ground-based application of 1080 poison are also used to control rabbits, an introduced grazing pest.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/1080-usage-in-new-zealand] By 1960, it had become the main poison used in rabbit control.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/1080-usage-in-new-zealand] The combination of aerial spreading and the use of carrots poisoned with 1080 enabled rabbit boards (which were responsible for rabbit destruction work) to reduce rabbit numbers in most areas by the early 1960s.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/1080-usage-in-new-zealand] The use of 1080 poison in New Zealand has been the subject of a long and complex debate.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/1080-usage-in-new-zealand] In general, the majority of conservationists and livestock farmers support the continued use of 1080 for pest control, while the hunting community, animal rights groups and antifluoride campaigners support a ban, although there are exceptions on both sides.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/1080-usage-in-new-zealand] Organised opposition is usually small-scale and localised to areas where aerial 1080 operations are carried out.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/1080-usage-in-new-zealand] Protest is generally peaceful, but there have been occasions where opponents have resorted to violence or sabotage.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/1080-usage-in-new-zealand] In August 2007, the Environmental Risk Management Authority released a review that gave new guidelines for the use of 1080 in New Zealand, and concluded the beneficial effects of pest eradication outweighed the risks.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/1080-usage-in-new-zealand] 1080 decomposes in natural water and soil into harmless compounds.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/1080-usage-in-new-zealand] In June 2011, the Parliamentary Commissioner for the Environment (PCE) released a report in favour of 1080 to control possums, rats, and stoats, especially in large and remote areas.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/1080-usage-in-new-zealand] It is seen as an effective poison for aerial spreading.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/1080-usage-in-new-zealand] The PCE came to a number of conclusions, including not having a moratorium on 1080 use, and setting up a Game Animal Council.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/1080-usage-in-new-zealand] In 2004, anti-1080 activist Phillip Anderton posed for the New Zealand media with a kiwi he claimed had been poisoned.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/1080-usage-in-new-zealand] An investigation revealed that Anderton lied to journalists and the public.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/1080-usage-in-new-zealand] He had used a kiwi that had been caught in a possum trap.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/1080-usage-in-new-zealand] In 2015, the New Zealand Police revealed that anonymous blackmail threats were sent to Fonterra and Federated Farmers saying that infant formula in supermarkets would be poisoned unless the use of 1080 was halted by the end of the month.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/1080-usage-in-new-zealand] Fonterra responded by working with the Ministry for Primary Industries to develop two high-throughput, validated test methods and then testing every tanker of milk and every batch of infant formula for 1080.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/1080-usage-in-new-zealand] The ensuing police response *Operation Concord* led to charges laid against 60-year-old businessman Jeremy Hamish Kerr, who pleaded guilty to two charges of blackmail and was sentenced to 8 years 6 months imprisonment.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/1080-usage-in-new-zealand] Kerr had developed a rival brand of poison called Feratox and made the threats for financial gain.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/1080-usage-in-new-zealand] The court heard that Kerr received around $100,000 a year in royalties from Feratox, but sales were dwindling.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/1080-usage-in-new-zealand] Biodegradable 1080 poison is the only pesticide currently registered for use on mainland New Zealand as suitable for aerial targeting of possums.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/1080-usage-in-new-zealand] While many research teams are actively seeking new and supplemental approaches to current technologies, no method has yet gained widespread acceptance as a viable alternative to 1080.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/1080-usage-in-new-zealand] New Zealand currently spends at least $8 million annually on improving existing pest control technology and developing new methods.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/1080-usage-in-new-zealand] According to the EPA's Annual Report on the Aerial Use of 1080, as of October 2011 there are currently over 50 research projects underway industry-wide to find improvements in the use of 1080, alternatives to 1080 and other related topics.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/1080-usage-in-new-zealand] Can the method increase populations of native species?
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/1080-usage-in-new-zealand] Can the method rapidly knock down erupting populations of pests?
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/1080-usage-in-new-zealand] Can the method be used on a large scale in remote areas?
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/1080-usage-in-new-zealand] Is the method sufficiently cost-effective?
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/1080-usage-in-new-zealand] Does the method leave residues in the environment?
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/1080-usage-in-new-zealand] Can by-kill from the method be minimised?
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/1080-usage-in-new-zealand] The Parliamentary Commissioner for the Environment's conclusion with regards to 1080 was, "It is not perfect, but given how controversial it remains, I for one expected that it would not be as effective and safe as it is".
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/1080-usage-in-new-zealand] The Parliamentary Commissioner reached the following conclusions regarding the possible alternatives to 1080 poison currently available in New Zealand.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/1080-usage-in-new-zealand] Pindone, diphacinone, and coumatetralyl are the first-generation anticoagulants most commonly used for pest control.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/1080-usage-in-new-zealand] They are generally very effective at controlling rats to keep their numbers low, but cannot effectively deal with sudden population surges.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/1080-usage-in-new-zealand] Anticoagulants break down very slowly in water and soil.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/1080-usage-in-new-zealand] They also accumulate in the liver tissue of live animals that have been exposed to the poison (either by eating bait or feeding on an animal that has eaten bait) and in carcasses.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/1080-usage-in-new-zealand] They are also the most inhumane of the poisons currently used.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/1080-usage-in-new-zealand] By-kill of native species is a significant risk from the use of first-generation anticoagulants.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/1080-usage-in-new-zealand] Different types of anticoagulants need to be rotated to avoid populations becoming bait-shy or building up resistance.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/1080-usage-in-new-zealand] Brodifacoum is a second-generation anticoagulant.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/1080-usage-in-new-zealand] It is licensed for killing possums and rats.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/1080-usage-in-new-zealand] Like 1080, it will kill stoats that feed on poisoned animals.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/1080-usage-in-new-zealand] It has been successfully used in aerial operations to completely eradicate possums, rats, and stoats on several offshore islands and fenced 'mainland islands' that are now sanctuaries for endangered animals, but it is not currently registered in New Zealand for general aerial use on the mainland.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/1080-usage-in-new-zealand] Brodifacoum takes a very long time to break down in soil and water and accumulates in the tissue of exposed animals for years.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/1080-usage-in-new-zealand] Consequently, there is a very high risk of by-kill: it is known to have killed at least 21 species of native birds, including kiwi, kākā, kākāriki and tūī.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/1080-usage-in-new-zealand] It is also widely considered a very inhumane poison.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/1080-usage-in-new-zealand] Cyanide has been used in New Zealand since the 1940s, and is licensed for killing possums and wallabies.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/1080-usage-in-new-zealand] It is a highly lethal, broad-spectrum poison that depletes cells of energy, quickly resulting in respiratory arrest and death.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/1080-usage-in-new-zealand] Ground-laid cyanide has killed native species and other animals in the past (including kiwi, kea, weka, and bats) and it takes only a tiny amount of cyanide to kill a human.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/1080-usage-in-new-zealand] While there are antidotes to cyanide poisoning, their effectiveness is controversial and the rapid action of the poison limits the time in which they can be used.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/1080-usage-in-new-zealand] Its effectiveness varies because of bait shyness.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/1080-usage-in-new-zealand] Cholecalciferol naturally occurs as vitamin D3 in many foods, including fish.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/1080-usage-in-new-zealand] It was developed as a poison to control rats and mice in the 1980s.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/1080-usage-in-new-zealand] It works by leaching calcium from the bones of the poisoned animal into its bloodstream, leading to organ failure.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/1080-usage-in-new-zealand] Cholecalciferol will reduce populations of possums and rats, but not stoats, since it does not bioaccumulate in animals.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/1080-usage-in-new-zealand] It breaks down readily in the environment and the risk of by-kill is considered to be low.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/1080-usage-in-new-zealand] Cholecalciferol is more expensive to produce than 1080.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/1080-usage-in-new-zealand] Some promising results have been obtained by combining cholecalciferol with other substances, such as aspirin, to make it more cost-effective and faster acting.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/1080-usage-in-new-zealand] Para-aminopropiophenone (PAPP) was developed to control stoats, weasels, and feral cats, and registered for use in New Zealand in 2011.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/1080-usage-in-new-zealand] It kills by preventing red blood cells from carrying oxygen.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/1080-usage-in-new-zealand] PAPP kills stoats directly, but not possums and rats.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/1080-usage-in-new-zealand] It is approved for use in paste form or in fresh minced meat, so will only provide effective stoat control as part of intensive ground control.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/1080-usage-in-new-zealand] The risk of by-kill is likely to be low since it does not leave residues in the environment.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/1080-usage-in-new-zealand] Zinc phosphide (microencapsulated zinc phosphide paste) has been widely used overseas for decades, predominantly to control rats and mice on agricultural land.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/1080-usage-in-new-zealand] It causes death by heart or respiratory failure.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/1080-usage-in-new-zealand] In August 2011, the New Zealand Environmental Protection Authority approved the import and manufacture of microencapsulated zinc phosphide (MZP paste) as an alternative to 1080 for the ground control of possums.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/1080-usage-in-new-zealand] The application was made by Pest Tech Limited, with support from Connovation Ltd, Lincoln University, and the Animal Health Board.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/1080-usage-in-new-zealand] It will be used as an additional vertebrate poison in certain situations.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/1080-usage-in-new-zealand] Unlike 1080, it cannot be used for aerial application.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/1080-usage-in-new-zealand] Sodium nitrite is a naturally occurring substance commonly used as a meat preservative, but toxic at higher doses.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/1080-usage-in-new-zealand] It kills in a similar way as PAPP, by reducing the ability of red blood cells to carry oxygen (methemoglobinemia).
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/1080-usage-in-new-zealand] Sodium nitrite is expected to be registered for use in for killing possums, but not rats.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/1080-usage-in-new-zealand] It will not control stoats because it will not knock down rat populations or bioaccumulate in poisoned animals.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/1080-usage-in-new-zealand] It does not leave residues in the environment and the risk of by-kill is expected to be low.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/1080-usage-in-new-zealand] Ground operations of which trapping is an important component have been shown to help populations of native birds.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/1080-usage-in-new-zealand] Possums, rats, and stoats can all be killed with traps.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/1080-usage-in-new-zealand] However, an intensive ground operation will typically involve trapping possums and stoats, but poisoning rats because there are so many more of them and they reproduce quickly.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/1080-usage-in-new-zealand] In a mass event, populations of rodents rapidly increase as much as ten-fold, and traps simply cannot be deployed rapidly enough or in sufficient numbers to knock them down.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/1080-usage-in-new-zealand] Some terrain is too rugged or dangerous for trapping, and trapping is not practical on a large scale.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/1080-usage-in-new-zealand] In one day, a single trapper can check traps on tens of hectares, whereas an aerial 1080 drop can cover tens of thousands of hectares.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/1080-usage-in-new-zealand] Once a trap has 'snapped', it will not catch another animal unless it is reset.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/1080-usage-in-new-zealand] Traps need to be checked and reset regularly, which makes them labour-intensive.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/1080-usage-in-new-zealand] Self-resetting traps, such as the Goodnature trap, are being developed and trialled, and could in the future significantly reduce labour costs and increase the cost-effectiveness of ground control operations.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/1080-usage-in-new-zealand] Twenty three species of native birds have been reported as having been killed by leg-hold traps, and many kiwi have suffered leg or beak damage.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/1080-usage-in-new-zealand] These traps are now required to be set up off the ground on conservation land where kiwi or weka (which are ground-dwelling birds) live.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/1080-usage-in-new-zealand] Biological control has been likened to the 'Holy Grail' of pest control by a number of sources, and was a major focus for research funding during the 1990s and 2000s in both New Zealand and Australia.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/1080-usage-in-new-zealand] Most of the methods proposed involved some form of genetic engineering, and if developed further would attract a great deal of public opposition.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/1080-usage-in-new-zealand] No biological control method has therefore yet gained widespread acceptance as a viable alternative to 1080.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/abel-tasman-national-park] The area of the park has seen human interaction for approximately 700 years, with evidence of habitation dating back to early Māori iwi such as Waitaha and Rapuwai during the early periods of Māori habitation in New Zealand.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/abel-tasman-national-park] Following the arrival of Pākehā in the 19th century, the area saw widespread deforestation, farming, and quarrying, significantly modifying the area's environment.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/abel-tasman-national-park] As a result of this, the park is one of the most modified landscapes of any of New Zealand's national parks, with management of the park largely focusing on regeneration and restoration of the traditional ecosystem.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/abel-tasman-national-park] The park was first established in 1942 to commemorate the 300th anniversary of Abel Tasman's 1642 visit in New Zealand, when he became the first European to sight the islands.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/abel-tasman-national-park] It has since been progressively expanded from its original borders, the most recent of which involved the addition of 7 hectares (17 acres) in Awaroa Inlet after a successful crowdfunding campaign.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/abel-tasman-national-park] The coastal area was inhabited for hundreds of years by Māori prior to the arrival of Europeans, with sites throughout the area occupied both seasonally and permanently.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/abel-tasman-national-park] In addition to harvesting food from the local forests, estuaries and waters, locals grew kūmara.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/abel-tasman-national-park] Historical records indicate a pā was established at Auckland Point by Pohea, who travelled there around 1450 from the Whanganui area.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/abel-tasman-national-park] From the mid-1500s Muaūpoko (formerly known as Ngāi Tara) occupied the area until the early 1600s, when they were ousted by Ngāti Tūmatakōkiri.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/abel-tasman-national-park] Ngāti Tūmatakōkiri were present when Abel Tasman reached Golden Bay / Mohua in 1642.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/abel-tasman-national-park] The park was founded in 1942, largely through the efforts of ornithologist and author Pérrine Moncrieff to have land reserved for the purpose.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/abel-tasman-national-park] Moncrieff served on the park board from 1943 to 1974.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/abel-tasman-national-park] The park was opened on 18 December 1942 to mark the 300th anniversary of Abel Tasman's visit.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/abel-tasman-national-park] Those in attendance at the opening ceremony at Tarakohe included Charles van der Plas, as personal representative of the Netherlands' Queen, Wilhelmina.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/abel-tasman-national-park] The idea for the park had been under consideration since June 1938.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/abel-tasman-national-park] The Crown set aside 15,225 hectares (37,622 acres), comprising 8,900 hectares (21,900 acres) of proposed state forest, 5,809 hectares (14,354 acres) of Crown land and 554 hectares (1,368 acres) of other reserve land for the national park.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/abel-tasman-national-park] The Golden Bay Cement Company donated the land where the Abel Tasman Monument and a memorial plaque was sited.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/abel-tasman-national-park] The area's primary historic interest was the visit of Tasman in 1642, D'Urville in 1827, and the New Zealand Company barques *Whitby* and *Will Watch*, and brig *Arrow* in 1841.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/abel-tasman-national-park] The site was also of significant botanical interest.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/abel-tasman-national-park] By 1946 the park had reached 15,534 hectares (38,386 acres) in area with additional land purchases.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/abel-tasman-national-park] A further 844 hectares (2,085 acres) at Tōtaranui, formerly owned by William Gibbs, was acquired from J S Campbell in 1949 and added to the park.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/abel-tasman-national-park] About 6,100 hectares (15,000 acres) have been added since.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/abel-tasman-national-park] In 2008 an extra 7.9 km2 (790 ha; 3.1 sq mi), including the formerly private land known as Hadfields Clearing, were added to the park.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/abel-tasman-national-park] In 2016, a further 7 hectares (17 acres) in Awaroa Inlet was purchased by New Zealanders in a crowdfunding campaign.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/abel-tasman-national-park] Covering an area of 237 km2 (92 sq mi; 59,000 acres), the park is the smallest of New Zealand's national parks.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/abel-tasman-national-park] It consists of forested, hilly country to the north of the valleys of the Tākaka and Riwaka Rivers, and is bounded to the north by the waters of Golden Bay / Mohua and Tasman Bay.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/abel-tasman-national-park] The park contains some of the islands off the coast including the Tata Islands in Golden Bay / Mohua, and Tonga Island, Motuareronui / Adele Island, and Fisherman Island in Tasman Bay.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/abel-tasman-national-park] The park does not extend beyond Mean High Water Mark on the adjacent coast.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/abel-tasman-national-park] Between Mean High Water and Mean Low Water Springs, the beaches are gazetted as a Scenic Reserve, covering 7.74 km2 (2.99 sq mi) in total.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/abel-tasman-national-park] The Tonga Island Marine Reserve adjoins part of the park.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/abel-tasman-national-park] The Abel Tasman Monument, though not located in the park, commemorates the first contact between Europeans and Māori and is located near the northern end of the park.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/abel-tasman-national-park] Abel Tasman National Park stands out from most other National parks of New Zealand, given that a large area of it has undergone extensive environmental modification in its history.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/abel-tasman-national-park] Early European settlers burned or cleared much of the forest, only to find that the soil was unsuitable for farming.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/abel-tasman-national-park] This practise not only destroyed much of the shrubland and forests, but also introduced invasive plants found throughout the modern-day park.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/abel-tasman-national-park] However, as time progresses, the original ecosystems and forests are slowly returning.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/abel-tasman-national-park] The park contains varied habitats, including coastal forests, sub-alpine bogs, and sand dunes.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/abel-tasman-national-park] As a result of this diversity, many different species can be found.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/abel-tasman-national-park] The islands of the park, in particular Tonga Island, Motuareronui / Adele Island and Fisherman Island which are the largest, have been disturbed less and have no introduced mammalian predators.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/abel-tasman-national-park] As a result the islands have species not found elsewhere in the park and there are more restrictions to visitor access.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/abel-tasman-national-park] Though much of the parkland is pasture or covered with shrubs, valley areas contain forests of rātā, mataī, miro and hinau.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/abel-tasman-national-park] Over 70 species of birds have been recorded in the park.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/abel-tasman-national-park] Some of the birds that can frequently be seen are petrels, shags, penguins, gulls, terns, and herons.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/abel-tasman-national-park] Possums, wild pigs, deer, and goats can also be seen in the park.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/abel-tasman-national-park] The Abel Tasman Coast Track is a popular tramping track that follows the coastline and is one of the Department of Conservation's Great Walks; the Abel Tasman Inland Track is less frequented.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/abel-tasman-national-park] Other walks in the park, such as the Wainui Falls Track are considered "short walks".
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/abel-tasman-national-park] Kayaking, camping and sightseeing are other activities.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/abel-tasman-national-park] Access to the park is usually via the small settlement of Mārahau or Kaiteriteri (by water taxi).
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/abel-tasman-national-park] The nearest large town is Motueka, 20 kilometres (12 mi) to the south.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/abel-tasman-national-park] Dogs (excepting guide dogs) are not allowed in the park.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/abel-tasman-national-park] The Department of Conservation administers the National Park.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/abel-tasman-national-park] The Scenic Reserve is administered by the Tasman District Council Chief Executive and Department of Conservation's Nelson / Marlborough Conservator.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/abel-tasman-national-park] Activities in adjoining coastal waters are Tasman District Council's responsibility.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/abel-tasman-national-park] These areas operate under separate regulations.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/abel-tasman-national-park] The Interior, consisting of the park areas further inland.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/abel-tasman-national-park] Park plans include ecological surveys, pest control, and protection of heritage areas and caves.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/abel-tasman-national-park] The Islands, encompassing all islands within the park, some of which are closed to the public. key priorities include keeping them free of invasive pests, reintroducing native species, and minimizing human impacts.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/abel-tasman-national-park] In 2012 Project Janszoon, a privately funded trust, was set up to restore the park's ecosystems.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/abel-tasman-national-park] The trust takes its name from Tasman's middle name *Janszoon*.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/abel-tasman-national-park] It is aiming to complete the restoration in time for the 400th anniversary of Tasman's visit and the park's 100th anniversary in 2042.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/abel-tasman-national-park] The Department of Conservation and Project Janszoon developed a free virtual visitor centre for downloading to smartphones or tablets.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/abel-tasman-national-park] The application provides information about the Park's history, its flora and fauna, points of interest, weather, walking tracks, and tides.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/abel-tasman-national-park] This virtual visitor centre is free of charge and can be found through the App Store or Google Play Store.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/ahuriri-conservation-park] The mountains, forests, tussock lands and river valleys are used for tramping, fishing kayaking, horse riding and hunting.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/ahuriri-conservation-park] Both the park and neighbouring Ben Avon Station are located near the Aoraki Mackenzie International Dark Sky Reserve, a dark-sky preserve, and are used for astronomy.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/ahuriri-conservation-park] The town is serviced by the tourist town of Omarama.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/ahuriri-conservation-park] The park was established in 2005, and includes the Birchwood Station leasehold farm the New Zealand Government bought back for NZ$10 million in 2004.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/ahuriri-conservation-park] It contained extensive wetlands that had remained largely undeveloped.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/ahuriri-conservation-park] Birchwood Station continued normal farming operations until the end of the leasehold in 2010.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/ahuriri-conservation-park] The road to the former Birchwood Station homestead stopped being regularly maintained by Waitaki District Council in 2011.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/ahuriri-conservation-park] In 2014, ecologist Peter Espie reported a decrease in native plant species in the park, and suggested introducing grazing management.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/ahuriri-conservation-park] Parts of the 2020 Disney film *Mulan* were filmed in the Ahuriri Valley near the conservation park, including the training camp scenes and some battle scenes.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/akaroa-marine-reserve] Akaroa Marine Reserve and the nearby Pōhatu Marine Reserve are no-take zones.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/akaroa-marine-reserve] The harbour as a whole has considerable natural values, and the fauna of the inner and outer harbour differs.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/akaroa-marine-reserve] There are pressures on the ecology from human activity, such as settlements on the edge of the harbour, and land and water-based industrial activity.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/akaroa-marine-reserve] The marine boundary of Akaroa Marine Reserve is almost entirely surrounded by Akaroa Taiāpure, which occupies the rest of the harbour and the ocean coast between the Akaroa and Pōhatu reserves.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/akaroa-marine-reserve] The taiāpure is a local fishing co-management tool for the harbour, which has customarily been of special significance to the hapū as a source of food for spiritual and cultural reasons.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/akaroa-marine-reserve] The taiāpure was established over 90 percent of the harbour in February 2006.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/akaroa-marine-reserve] It allows Te Rūnanga o Ngāi Tahu (tribal council) and other fisheries stakeholders to have a say in how the harbour is managed.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/akaroa-marine-reserve] Fishing can continue in taiāpure, subject to rules and regulations.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/akaroa-marine-reserve] The taiāpure complements the reserve (the remaining 10% of the harbour), as does Pōhatu Marine Reserve just outside the harbour entrance, in Pōhatu / Flea Bay, plus Lyttelton Harbour's Port Levy Mātaitai Reserve and Rāpaki Mātaitai Reserve.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/akaroa-marine-reserve] A *mātaitai* is a permanent reserve created in areas of traditional importance to Māori for customary food gathering.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/akaroa-marine-reserve] The two marine reserves are total no-take areas, whereas the taiāpure and mātaitai are fishing enabling and not about the protection of marine life.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/akaroa-marine-reserve] Indeed, the *tangata tiaki* (marine guardian) has the power to override fishing regulations, and moreover, the taking of kelp by one pāua farmer is enshrined in the taiāpure legislation.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/akaroa-marine-reserve] The Akaroa Taiāpure Management Committee is a non-elected group largely made up of Ngāi Tahu representatives and a range of fisheries interest groups, including recreational, commercial, marine farmers and marine tourism operators.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/akaroa-marine-reserve] This committee has no control over the number of recreational anglers, hence no control over the total number of fish and shellfish taken.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/akaroa-marine-reserve] Throughout the 1980s and 1990s, people with local knowledge knew that fish stocks were nowhere near as plentiful as they once were.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/akaroa-marine-reserve] Māori who had fished the harbour for decades had lost the opportunity of fishing freely along its shoreline.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/akaroa-marine-reserve] The *rūnanga* (committee of senior decision-makers of an *iwi* (tribal group) or *hapū* (family, district groups or community)) knew that pollution and over-fishing had diminished the area of available *mahinga kai* (traditional food gathering areas) within the harbour.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/akaroa-marine-reserve] Pollution includes sewage, farm and sub-division run-off as well as algal blooms.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/akaroa-marine-reserve] Forest and Bird carried out exploratory dives in Akaroa Harbour in 1990.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/akaroa-marine-reserve] The Akaroa Harbour Marine Protection Society formally proposed the establishment of a 560-hectare (1,400-acre) marine reserve in 1996.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/akaroa-marine-reserve] The proposal was divisive and led to a two-decade battle that pitted a small group of vocal and determined local residents and divers against recreational anglers, *rūnanga*, commercial fishers and one aquaculturalist.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/akaroa-marine-reserve] The local residents wanted a no-take area in the eastern waters of the outer harbour to acts as a breeding pool and as place for dolphins to feed.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/akaroa-marine-reserve] Recreational anglers argued "that's where we fish in a northeasterly".
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/akaroa-marine-reserve] Te Runanga o Ngāi Tahu claimed strong ties to the area, naming it Te Whata o Kōkiro (meaning the food store-house of Kokiro).
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/akaroa-marine-reserve] When the marine reserve idea was first mooted, commercial fishing was a part of Akaroa's economy and commercial fishers strongly opposed it.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/akaroa-marine-reserve] During the long battle, fish stock declined, and so did commercial fishing.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/akaroa-marine-reserve] The original proposal called for a reserve within the harbour.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/akaroa-marine-reserve] Fishers counteracted that proposal by applying for and getting a smaller 215 hectares (530 acres) hectares reserve to be located outside of the harbour, at sheltered bay named Pōhatu / Flea Bay.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/akaroa-marine-reserve] While eco-tourism operators were pleased to have something to show to tourists, local iwi continued to express concerns that marine reserves hindered their traditional rights to harvest from the sea.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/akaroa-marine-reserve] Meanwhile, the local residents group continued to advocate for a reserve within the harbour.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/akaroa-marine-reserve] The Fisheries Act 1996 Part 9 Section 174–175 provides for the establishment of taiāpure/fisheries co-management by local people who care about and have strong ties to an area.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/akaroa-marine-reserve] In January 2004, the Māori Land Court tribunal made a recommendation to the Minister of Fisheries that a taiāpure be granted over the whole of Akaroa Harbour bar one small area subject to the, at that time, proposed Akaroa Marine Reserve.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/akaroa-marine-reserve] Judge Wainwright saw no reason why the two could not live together.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/akaroa-marine-reserve] However, this recommendation was successfully appealed by the local pāua farmer and kelp harvester, who claimed a taiāpure would compromise his business.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/akaroa-marine-reserve] The High Court sent the case back to the tribunal to gather further evidence about whether the whole of Akaroa Harbour does or does not come within the concept of "littoral coastal waters" of "special cultural significance" to the rūnanga.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/akaroa-marine-reserve] The pāua farmer eventually reached an understanding with Ngāi Tahu, ending years of argument.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/akaroa-marine-reserve] He has been granted the rights to harvest giant bladder kelp (*Macrocystis pyrifera*), which he uses to feed the pāua at the Akaroa Paua Farm and also to make garden fertiliser and kelp pepper.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/akaroa-marine-reserve] In contrast, the East Otago Taiāpure explicitly prohibits the harvesting of kelp.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/akaroa-marine-reserve] That ban does not extend to unattached beach-cast kelp.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/akaroa-marine-reserve] There are environmental concerns in Akaroa Harbour regarding the ecological disruption caused by kelp harvesting to wild pāua and other *kaimoana* (sea food).
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/akaroa-marine-reserve] The taiāpure was established in February 2006, but the marine reserve took eight more years.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/akaroa-marine-reserve] Conservation Minister Kate Wilkinson declined the application for the reserve in 2010 on the grounds that it would adversely affect recreational fishing.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/akaroa-marine-reserve] The decision was challenged in the High Court and was quashed in a 2012 ruling.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/akaroa-marine-reserve] In terms of actual numbers, the two separate consultation processes for the application had attracted more support than opposition.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/akaroa-marine-reserve] In April 2013 Conservation Minister Nick Smith announced the approval of the reserve but at the reduced size of 465 hectares (1,150 acres).
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/akaroa-marine-reserve] Smith believed the battle had gone on for too long.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/akaroa-marine-reserve] The size was reduced to take into account the concerns about customary and recreational fishing.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/akaroa-marine-reserve] Subsequently, the size was finalised as 512 hectares (1,270 acres).
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/akaroa-marine-reserve] Environment Minister Amy Adams expressed an aspiration for the next step to be integrating the local management of taiāpure and reserve so the two mechanisms work together.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/akaroa-marine-reserve] New Zealand fishing rules place reduced bag limits on many fish species and prohibit shellfish gathering in specific areas.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/akaroa-marine-reserve] Tangata tiaki (marine guardians) are appointed for Ōnuku Runanga *rōhe moana* (defined customary fishing area) by the Minister of Primary Industries.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/akaroa-marine-reserve] The tangata tiaki (also known as kaitiaki) receive training in bylaws, what quantities of various species can be taken, dates or seasons recommended for harvest, size limits and methods of harvest.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/akaroa-marine-reserve] Fishers can get a kaitiaki permit from the tangata tiaki granting permission to take over and above the catch limit, and under the legal size.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/akaroa-marine-reserve] This permit, colloquially called a "chit", is given for *tangihanga* (funeral), *hui* (gathering) and other occasions.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/akaroa-marine-reserve] In addition to upping catch limits, the kaitiaki has the power to override other fishing regulations.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/akaroa-marine-reserve] In 2018, the Department of Conservation trialled a baited underwater video study, which provided a snapshot of the fish communities both within and outside the Akaroa and Pōhatu marine reserves.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/akaroa-marine-reserve] A total of 28 fish species were identified, demonstrating that the baited underwater video technique is an effective method for examining the size and relative abundance of these species.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/akaroa-marine-reserve] The study found notable differences in the relative abundances and sizes of blue cod and blue moki in the marine reserves when compared to three taiāpure control areas.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/akaroa-marine-reserve] However, since there is no baseline data for Akaroa Marine Reserve, it would be hasty to link these spatial variations to their protection status.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/akaroa-marine-reserve] Nonetheless, the results indicated an increase in the abundance and size of blue cod and moki at Pōhatu reserve compared to earlier studies, and that is likely due to the protection from direct fishing pressure.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/akaroa-marine-reserve] In 2021, a three-year initiative called *Iongairo* was launched to supply data that aids in the management of customary fishing zones and enhances understanding of marine reserves in Te Pātaka o Rākaihautū/Banks Peninsula.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/akaroa-marine-reserve] *Iongairo* focused on identifying and evaluating important habitats—including rock, sand, and mud—and key species such as pāua, mussels, and various types of seaweed.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/akaroa-marine-reserve] Additionally, it examined the effects of human activities on the environment.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/akaroa-marine-reserve] Methods included baited underwater cameras, towed and dropped cameras, along with sediment grabs.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/akaroa-marine-reserve] The outcome is an interactive online map showcasing the seafloor.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/akatarawa-forest] The park is owned and managed by Greater Wellington Regional Council, making it one of the largest landowners in New Zealand.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/akatarawa-forest] Akatarawa is a Māori name meaning 'Trailing vines'.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/akatarawa-forest] Activities include cycling, hunting, fishing, horse riding, 4WD-vehicle trips and trail biking, including at the Karapoti Gorge.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/akatarawa-forest] Akatarawa Forest has ancient northern rātā which predate human habitation of New Zealand, including one tree which is believed to be 1100 years old.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/akatarawa-forest] Some of these trees are wider than Tāne Mahuta.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/akatarawa-forest] One is largest rātā tree in New Zealand, at 39 metres tall.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/akatarawa-forest] Greater Wellington Regional Council carried out a 1080 dropping programme in 2013 to reduce pest species.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/akatarawa-forest] A trailbiker was seriously injured in the park in July 2017.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/akatarawa-forest] A dirt-biker was rescued from the forest in February 2021.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/akatarawa-forest] Between December 2017 and August 2018, a 1.7 kilometre zig-zag track that is part of the Cannon Point Walkway was closed to the public due to a disagreement between Upper Hutt City Council and a private landowner over land access.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/akatarawa-forest] In early 2021, Forest and Bird campaigned for Upper Hutt City Council to keep a 35-hectare block as a wildlife corridor and reserve, connecting Akatarawa Forest with Wainuiomata.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/akatarawa-forest] In July 2021, a further 1080 operation was carried out in 2021 to combat a resurgence in possum numbers.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/alice-eaves-scenic-reserve] The area was previously a defensive pā, built by Te Kawerau sub-tribes, occupied until as recently as 1827.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/alice-eaves-scenic-reserve] Ngāti Pāoa ceded the land to the Crown on 5 January 1854, which was subsequently granted to an Austrian, Captain Martin Krippner, in 1860.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/alice-eaves-scenic-reserve] In the 1870s, Major de Grut took over the land until it was sold to the Eaves family in 1919.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/alice-eaves-scenic-reserve] The local Lions began making tracks, building bridges and removing invasive weeds, and the Reserve was formally opened by the Lions Club Chairman, Don Woods on 10 December 1960.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/alice-eaves-scenic-reserve] The daughters of Alice and Edward Eaves were present.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/alice-eaves-scenic-reserve] A series of pedestrian walkways have been constructed through the reserve, as well as a wooden look out point over Orewa Beach that was built in 1997.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/alice-eaves-scenic-reserve] The reserve includes kauri trees as old as 300 years.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/alice-eaves-scenic-reserve] In addition, the bush contains native trees such as tōtara, mataī, kahikatea, pūriri, rata, karaka, rimu, rewarewa, nīkau and taraire.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/alice-eaves-scenic-reserve] A number of these trees can be identified by labels along the walkway.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/alice-eaves-scenic-reserve] Several small streams feed the Nukumea Stream, which marks the reserve's southern boundary.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/alice-eaves-scenic-reserve] The status of the land is Scenic Reserve 19(1)(a) and under the Reserves Act, the management is the responsibility of the Hibiscus and Bays Local Board, elected representatives under the Governing Body, Auckland Council.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/alice-eaves-scenic-reserve] The role of the Board is to make decisions on local matters such as the maintenance and upgrading of facilities, caring for the environment, preservation of heritage and supporting activities in the area.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/alice-eaves-scenic-reserve] In June 2019, the Reserve was required by the Auckland Council to close to the public due to the danger of kauri dieback caused by the spread of a pathogen in contaminated soil possibly being carried on the soles of shoes.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/alice-eaves-scenic-reserve] Lauri Rands from the Eaves Bush Appreciation Society expressed sadness but noted that protection of the 800-year-old kauri in the Reserve was a good example of the importance of taking this action.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/alice-eaves-scenic-reserve] The lower track on the Reserve was re-opened on 30 August 2020 with a hygiene station at the entrance and exit to allow shoes to be cleaned.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/alice-eaves-scenic-reserve] It was noted at the time, that the upper tracks were scheduled for re-opening late in 2021.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/alice-eaves-scenic-reserve] Hibiscus and Bays Local Board Chair Gary Brown expressed delight at the reopening and appreciation to the Council for the work they had done to bring this about.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/alice-eaves-scenic-reserve] He also acknowledged the voluntary contribution of the Eaves Bush Appreciation Group who had worked for years to weed, plant and trap pests.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/alice-eaves-scenic-reserve] Members of this group were the first to walk the re-opened section.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/alice-eaves-scenic-reserve] The Greenways project proposed by the Auckland Council in 2016 had been prioritised by the Hisbiscus and Bays Local Board in 2017 and a feasibility report for implementing walking and cycling connections between the Reserve and Hatfields Beach was completed in 2018.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/ambury-regional-park] The park is a working sheep and dairy farm with a woolshed and milking shed.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/ambury-regional-park] There are also goats, cows, pigs, chickens, turkey, rabbits and peacocks.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/ambury-regional-park] Areas of the park are leased to the Mangere Pony Club, and the Ambury Park Centre for Riding Therapy, a charity which opened in 1985, which provides physiological and psychological therapy through horse riding.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/ambury-regional-park] The parks hosts the Ambury Farm Day each year.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/ambury-regional-park] It is the largest annual event organised by Auckland Council, and gives families free access to a working farm.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/ambury-regional-park] The park covers 85 hectares (210 acres) of low-lying volcanic land on the shores of the upper Manukau Harbour.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/ambury-regional-park] It includes both camping coastline, grazed farming paddocks, wetlands, saltmarshes and small areas of native forest.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/ambury-regional-park] Much of Ambury Regional Park formed approximately 50,000 years ago, during an eruption of Māngere Mountain.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/ambury-regional-park] There are several examples of basalt lava flows, originating from the Māngere Mountain about 18,000 years ago.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/ambury-regional-park] Most other lava flows around Auckland have been destroyed during urban development.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/ambury-regional-park] Large numbers of migratory shorebirds visit Ambury Regional Park and the surrounding areas of the Manukau Harbour, with an estimated number of 28,000 tōrea and 1,200 ngutuparore (wrybills) migrating north from the South Island after breeding over the winter.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/ambury-regional-park] During summer months, an estimated 12,000 kuaka (bar-tailed godwits) and 9,000 huahou (red knots) spend summer months in the vicinity of the park.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/ambury-regional-park] Kōtuku ngutupapa (royal spoonbill) also migrate to the area.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/ambury-regional-park] Birdwatchers have identified a total of 86 birds in the park including little shags, and white-faced herons.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/ambury-regional-park] In 2015, a vegetation survey identified 40 native species in Ambury Regional Park, including the nationally vulnerable species *Geranium retrorsum*, and oioi-coastal needle grass, only rarely seen in saline volcanic soil in the Auckland Region.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/ambury-regional-park] There is an extensive history of Māori settlement in the Māngere Mountain area, and there are 95 archaeological sites around the park.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/ambury-regional-park] During the mid-19th century, the area was converted to farmland.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/ambury-regional-park] In 1882, the Ambury English & Co milk company established a creamery on a 260 acres (110 ha) farm on Wallace Road.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/ambury-regional-park] In the late 1960s, the Māngere sewage treatment was established on the shores of the Manukau Harbour.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/ambury-regional-park] Over 500 hectares (1,200 acres) of oxidation ponds were decommissioned, 13 kilometres (8.1 mi) of shoreline were restored, beaches were constructed, and 27,000 trees were planted in New Zealand's largest coastal restoration project, which was officially completed in 2005.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/ambury-regional-park] During the 1960s, the Auckland Regional Authority purchased land adjacent to the Māngere sewage treatment plant as a buffer.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/ambury-regional-park] From une 1973, local community groups were able to user the land, and in 1977 an educational farm was established at the site.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/ambury-regional-park] Ambury Regional Park was officially opened on 26 September 1987.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/ambury-regional-park] In 1985, a fuel pipeline between Marsden Point and Auckland Airport was laid through the park.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/ambury-regional-park] The route is marked by white fenceposts, farm gate tags and triangular marine markers.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/ambury-regional-park] In December 1986, the Ambury Regional Park was the site of a large-scale Mongrel Mob convention, where over 300 members attended, during which gang members helped complete the rock retaining walls along the Manukau waterfront.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/ambury-regional-park] A kidnapping and sexual assault at this event became national news.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/ambury-regional-park] The annual Ambury Farm Day began in 1988.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/ambury-regional-park] By the early 2000s, the park had become a popular school excursion, with 3-4 schools booked per week visiting the working farm.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/ambury-regional-park] A new concept plan for the park was developed in 2009, which included linking it up to nearby walk and cycling tracks.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/ambury-regional-park] By that stage, 25,000 people were visiting the park each year outside of the annual farm day.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/ambury-regional-park] By the late 2010s, around 400,000 people had begun visiting the park annually.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/ambury-regional-park] There are a range of facilities, including public toilets and barbecues.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/ambury-regional-park] The campground can accommodate up to 60 people.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/ambury-regional-park] The park is connected by walkway and cycleway to the Māngere Bridge to Onehunga in the north-east along Kiwi Esplanade, and the Ihumātao to the south.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/ambury-regional-park] It is within walking distance to the nearest bus stop, and the nearest train station is Onehunga railway station.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/arthur-s-pass-national-park] Land in Arthur's Pass and the Otira Gorge was originally set aside under the Lands Act 1885 and the Scenery Preservation Act of 1903.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/arthur-s-pass-national-park] This land later became the foundation for the national park.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/arthur-s-pass-national-park] After the Midland railway line was built, train trips from Christchurch to the Otira Gorge began in 1926 when the Railway Department organised day excursions for hundreds of tourists.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/arthur-s-pass-national-park] Unfortunately, native flowers were popular souvenirs.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/arthur-s-pass-national-park] Some individuals chose to cut down trees to obtain rātā blooms.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/arthur-s-pass-national-park] As a result, there was a large push to establish national park status for the area.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/arthur-s-pass-national-park] Arthur′s Pass National Park was established in 1929, becoming the first national park in the South Island and the third in New Zealand.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/arthur-s-pass-national-park] Underfunding meant that national park status was initially in name only: it took a number of years for the flora and fauna in the park to be fully protected.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/arthur-s-pass-national-park] The first park ranger at Arthur's Pass National Park was Charles Edward Warden, who was appointed in 1929 on the establishment of the park and served until November 1937.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/arthur-s-pass-national-park] Warden lived in a cottage at 'Tin Town' inside the park and was paid an honorarium for his work, which included marking and maintaining tracks, public relations and advice to visitors about the park, and trying to stop tourists from destroying or removing plants.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/arthur-s-pass-national-park] In 1942, Warden was appointed to the Arthur's Pass National Park Board of Control.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/arthur-s-pass-national-park] The first full-time ranger at the park, Martin Burke, was employed in 1938.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/arthur-s-pass-national-park] Ray Cleland, ranger from 1950 to 1958, made many improvements in the park.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/arthur-s-pass-national-park] He established a museum, oversaw building of a park ranger's house and workshop, and helped establish a 48-bunk youth hostel and a chapel.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/arthur-s-pass-national-park] Walking tracks for less-fit visitors were created along with camping and picnic sites and more information signs.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/arthur-s-pass-national-park] Cleland attempted to control plant and animal pests and had to deal with "boisterous" visitors on excursion trains.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/arthur-s-pass-national-park] Cleland is remembered in the name of a street (Cleland Place) in Arthur's Pass village.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/arthur-s-pass-national-park] In 1901, the Riversdale Flats were gazetted for inclusion in Arthur's Pass National Park, However, when the park was created in 1929, the 1,000 hectares of the Riversdale Flats were excluded.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/arthur-s-pass-national-park] These were then incorporated into the Mount White Station lease.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/arthur-s-pass-national-park] In 2007, the Arthur's Pass National Park plan recommended the inclusion of the Riversdale Flats.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/arthur-s-pass-national-park] In late 2021, the status of whether the Riversdale Flats should remain within the Mount White lease or be incorporated into Arthur's Pass National Park was before the courts.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/arthur-s-pass-national-park] The Department of Conservation operates a depot, administration and information centre in Arthur's Pass village.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/arthur-s-pass-national-park] It has been proposed that facilities should be developed to encourage more visitors to stay the night.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/arthur-s-pass-national-park] Achieving this would require more high-end accommodation and amenities to be built.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/arthur-s-pass-national-park] The report notes that visitors peak over summer.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/arthur-s-pass-national-park] There is a lack of longer day walk options in the park and all–weather amenities.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/arthur-s-pass-national-park] The report also suggested that a cable car would be popular to access the tops of the mountains as would hot pools in the village and an upgraded visitor centre.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/arthur-s-pass-national-park] The Department of Conservation had yet to make a decision on the development of Arthur's Pass National Park by June 2021.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/arthur-s-pass-national-park] From 2019, most international visitors to New Zealand have been charged an 'International Visitor Conservation and Tourism Levy' (IVL).
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/arthur-s-pass-national-park] At Arthur's Pass National Park, $300,000 from the IVL fund has been allocated for "delivery of a collaborative co-design approach to support the development of a well-functioning regional visitor destination".
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/arthur-s-pass-national-park] Arthur′s Pass National Park is bisected by State Highway 73.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/arthur-s-pass-national-park] The road passes through Arthur's Pass village and the mountain pass with the same name over the Southern Alps at a height of 920 metres above sea level.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/arthur-s-pass-national-park] The National Park is located within a few hours of driving from Christchurch, the largest city on the South Island of New Zealand.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/arthur-s-pass-national-park] The park is split by the main divide of the South Island.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/arthur-s-pass-national-park] The eastern side is typically drier and consists of mountain beech forest and wide riverbeds, while the western side contains dense rainforest (which includes mixed podocarp and rata).
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/arthur-s-pass-national-park] Much of the geography was formed by ancient glacial action, forming flat bottomed U-shaped valleys.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/arthur-s-pass-national-park] In the middle is a high range, consisting of large, snow-covered peaks and scree slopes.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/arthur-s-pass-national-park] The coldest temperature recorded in Arthurs Pass was −18.9 °C (−2 °F) at Bealey on 19 July 1878.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/arthur-s-pass-national-park] The township of Arthur's Pass is situated on State Highway 73 within the park.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/arthur-s-pass-national-park] It has a store, visitor accommodation, restaurants and a petrol station, and is the starting point for many tracks and walks.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/arthur-s-pass-national-park] The resident population of Arthur's Pass in 2018 was 48 people.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/arthur-s-pass-national-park] The first national park visitor centre was built in Arthur′s Pass in 1959, with the help of the Christchurch Wanderers Tramping Club.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/arthur-s-pass-national-park] It was designed by Christchurch architect Paul Pascoe and used local stone to reflect the geology of the national park.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/arthur-s-pass-national-park] As well as Department of Conservation offices, the building housed museum displays on the history of Arthur's Pass (including Richard Seddon's stagecoach) and archives detailing the history of the National Park.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/arthur-s-pass-national-park] In 2019 the building was declared earthquake prone, and the visitor centre was moved to a portacabin across the road.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/arthur-s-pass-national-park] The cost to upgrade the building to the required standard was estimated at NZ$3 million.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/arthur-s-pass-national-park] The plant habitats in Arthurs Pass National Park are quite different on each side of the Main Divide.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/arthur-s-pass-national-park] The eastern side of the park has less rainfall and braided riverbeds, supporting red beech and mountain beech forests with little understorey.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/arthur-s-pass-national-park] Drier valley floors are dominated by grasses, sedges and tussock surrounded by shrubland of matagouri and hebes.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/arthur-s-pass-national-park] Above the bush line are areas of snow tussock, alpine herb fields and scree slopes.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/arthur-s-pass-national-park] The western side of the park has high rainfall, river gorges and dense rainforest.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/arthur-s-pass-national-park] A 2004 survey found only three whio (blue ducks) in the Mingha and Deception Valley area of the park, and by 2021 it was estimated that there were fewer than 3,000 whio left in New Zealand.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/arthur-s-pass-national-park] Seventeen birds were released into the Mingha–Deception Valley area in March 2021, and monitored stoat traps help reduce predation on them.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/arthur-s-pass-national-park] The rarest of New Zealand's kākāriki species, the orange-fronted parakeet (Cyanoramphus malherbi) has twice been declared extinct.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/arthur-s-pass-national-park] It is only found in Arthur's Pass National Park and the Lake Sumner Forest Park and is critically endangered.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/arthur-s-pass-national-park] The Department of Conservation works with Ngāi Tahu to protect the kākāriki karaka, which is a taonga species for the iwi.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/arthur-s-pass-national-park] It is most commonly seen in the Hawdon and Poulter valleys.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/arthur-s-pass-national-park] The bird nests in holes in trees, making it vulnerable to predators.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/arthur-s-pass-national-park] Predator control has been carried out in the Arthur's Pass National Park since 2005.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/arthur-s-pass-national-park] Since 2019, the wild population has increased from about 150-200 birds to around 360 birds.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/arthur-s-pass-national-park] Kea are regularly seen in both the park and the township.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/arthur-s-pass-national-park] Kea also visit the local ski fields (Porters, Cheeseman, Broken River, Craigieburn and Temple Basin).
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/arthur-s-pass-national-park] Kea are at risk of predation by stoats, possums and feral cats.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/arthur-s-pass-national-park] They have also learned to interact with visitors, scavenging or scrounging food and getting into rubbish.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/arthur-s-pass-national-park] This habituates the kea to human food and puts it at risk of eating bait laid down for predators.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/arthur-s-pass-national-park] In 2022, The Department of Conservation and OSPRI (a company working to manage farm animal diseases) funded research near Arthur's Pass to test whether bird repellents would stop kea from interacting with 1080 bait.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/arthur-s-pass-national-park] The year-long study showed that the repellents were ineffective.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/arthur-s-pass-national-park] The kea is an intelligent, curious and playful bird.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/arthur-s-pass-national-park] When kea visit Arthur's Pass village to scavenge food, they walk across the road or perch on moving cars, sometimes falling off.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/arthur-s-pass-national-park] A conservationist at Arthur's Pass states that between 2020 and 2022, 12 kea were killed by cars including eight in Arthur's Pass village.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/arthur-s-pass-national-park] Visitors are encouraged not to feed kea and to dispose of their rubbish carefully.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/arthur-s-pass-national-park] Kea also have a habit of eating lead from building flashings and nails, which is toxic and can kill them.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/arthur-s-pass-national-park] In 2018 a project was undertaken to remove lead from houses at Arthur's Pass to reduce the risk to kea.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/arthur-s-pass-national-park] The great spotted kiwi or roroa (*Apteryx maxima*) lives in mountainous beech forest near Arthur's Pass village, which is one of three natural populations of the bird.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/arthur-s-pass-national-park] Their habitat in the National Park means they are less prone to predation than other species of kiwi, and the total population, though classed as vulnerable, is relatively stable at around 14,000 birds.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/arthur-s-pass-national-park] Great spotted kiwi at Arthur's Pass National Park are occasionally killed or injured by cars as they cross the road (and one was killed by a train).
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/arthur-s-pass-national-park] Weka are becoming more common in the western side of the park and occasionally in the Edwards Valley.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/arthur-s-pass-national-park] Weka used to be common in the park but by the 1920s had disappeared, possibly due to predation by weasels.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/arthur-s-pass-national-park] From 1961, there were several attempts to reintroduce weka to the Andrews Valley, Taramakau Valley and Poulter Valley areas in the park with birds sourced from the Chatham Islands and the West Coast.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/arthur-s-pass-national-park] In 1968 it was announced that West Coast weka appeared to have been successfully re-established in the Taramakau Valley.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/arthur-s-pass-national-park] Further sightings in the next few years confirmed that the population was growing.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/arthur-s-pass-national-park] They have slowly expanded their territory and predator control has allowed the population to expand towards Arthur's Pass Village.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/arthur-s-pass-national-park] The mohua or yellowhead is a small bird that nests and roosts in holes in trees.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/arthur-s-pass-national-park] It was formerly common in South Island beech forests, but populations in the Arthur's Pass area declined by the 1980s due to predation by rats and stoats.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/arthur-s-pass-national-park] The remaining small population was wiped out in 1999–2000 when predator numbers increased dramatically after the beech trees produced huge numbers of seeds (known as a beech mast).
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/arthur-s-pass-national-park] In 2022, the Department of Conservation released 41 birds into the Poulter Valley in Arthur's Pass National Park in an attempt to re-establish the mohua population.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/arthur-s-pass-national-park] In 2025 a large beech mast was predicted, so the Department of Conservation increased its predator control efforts in the park and other locations.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/arthur-s-pass-national-park] Trail cameras show that deer, pigs, possums, feral cats, stoats and mice have been seen at Arthur's Pass.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/arthur-s-pass-national-park] These animals threaten native wildlife in various ways: habitat destruction, eating birds or their eggs, and eating the food sources of native birds.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/arthur-s-pass-national-park] For example, it was discovered that feral cats in the park eat short-horned grasshoppers (Acrididae).
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/arthur-s-pass-national-park] The Department of Conservation controls rats, stoats and possums in the park using aerial drops of 1080 (sodium fluoroacetate) and ground control methods such as traps and toxins in bait stations.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/arthur-s-pass-national-park] The park is popular for tramping, skiing, hunting and mountaineering.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/arthur-s-pass-national-park] The mountains around Arthur's Pass contain very challenging terrain.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/arthur-s-pass-national-park] The peaks are highly exposed to the weather, the tracks are often very steep, and are often marked only by poles strung across a rocky landscape.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/arthur-s-pass-national-park] Below the tree line the bush is dense and thick.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/arthur-s-pass-national-park] In common with many alpine areas the weather is subject to frequent and sudden change.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/arthur-s-pass-national-park] There have been numerous incidents where trampers have been unprepared for the harsh and variable conditions, and Arthur's Pass National Park consequently has a reputation as one of the most dangerous national parks in New Zealand.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/arthur-s-pass-national-park] The Department of Conservation provides 31 mountain huts in Arthur's Pass National Park, on both sides of the Main Divide.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/arthur-s-pass-national-park] For a small fee, the huts provide shelter and basic facilities for trampers, climbers and others visiting the mountains.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/arthur-s-pass-national-park] There are also privately-owned huts or lodges in the area.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/arthur-s-pass-national-park] Avalanche Peak is the only peak in Arthur's Pass National Park that is marked by a poled route to the summit.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/arthur-s-pass-national-park] The route is steep and climbs 1,100 metres vertical from the Arthur's Pass village.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/arthur-s-pass-national-park] On a clear day, there are good views of the Southern Alps.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/arthur-s-pass-national-park] The Devils Punchbowl waterfall is located close to the northern end of Arthur′s Pass Village.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/arthur-s-pass-national-park] The short walk through beech forest to the waterfall and back can be completed in under two hours.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/arthur-s-pass-national-park] The track climbs a well maintained track to the base of the 131 metre waterfall, where there is a viewing platform.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/arthur-s-pass-national-park] Mount Rolleston is one of the highest peaks in the National Park. it is 2271 meters tall.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/arthur-s-pass-national-park] It is a popular mountain to climb and there are multiple ways to climb it The Rolleston Glacier has melted significantly and the degree of the melt in 2011 would be a 1-in-100-year event under natural conditions, but due to climate change this has become a 1-in-8-year event.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/arthur-s-pass-national-park] This is a popular day trip within Arthur's Pass National Park.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/arthur-s-pass-national-park] It is an easy 2.5 hour walk up to the Bealey Spur Hut, with views over the Wamaikariri Basin and surrounding mountains.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/arthur-s-pass-national-park] O'Malleys track starts at State Highway 73 and follows the Waimakariri River, crossing Turkey Flat to Anti Crow Hut then on to Carrington Hut.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/arthur-s-pass-national-park] This takes the average fit walker five hours.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/arthur-s-pass-national-park] From Carrington Hut, it is possible to climb Harman Pass (1315m) and cross the Southern Alps.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/arthur-s-pass-national-park] Another trip from Carrington Hut is to continue following the Waimakariri River to Waimakariri Falls Hut, at 1,290 metres above sea level.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/arthur-s-pass-national-park] Various mountaineering trips can be taken from here into the higher mountains of the National Park.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/arthur-s-pass-national-park] From Anti Crow Hut it is also possible to cross the Wamakariri River and walk up the Crow river towards Crow Hut which sits at 1020 metres above sea level.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/arthur-s-pass-national-park] This challenging tramping trip travels up the Edwards River, crosses two alpine passes and then travels down the Hawdon River.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/arthur-s-pass-national-park] The Department of Conservation describes it as "...best of Arthur's Pass National Park's stunning alpine landscapes.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/arthur-s-pass-national-park] The hanging valley at Walker Pass is reached via Taruahuna Pass and the steep climb up to Tarn Col".
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/arthur-s-pass-national-park] This is typically a two night and three day tramp with stops at Edwards Hut and Hawdon Hut.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/arthur-s-pass-national-park] It is suitable for very experienced tramping groups only.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/arthur-s-pass-national-park] The Andrews-Poulter is a popular non-technical trip on the eastern side of Arthur′s Pass National Park.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/arthur-s-pass-national-park] It crosses two passes, the first being the Casey saddle which is surrounded by beech forest.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/arthur-s-pass-national-park] From there, the track leads to Casey Hut.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/arthur-s-pass-national-park] The second day travels along the river flats of the Poulter before climbing through the beech forest to the Binser saddle and then descending to the carpark near the Andrews shelter in the Mt White road.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/arthur-s-pass-national-park] The Casey Hut built in 1969 burnt down in October 2015.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/arthur-s-pass-national-park] In 2019, two anonymous donors provided $250,000 for the hut to be rebuilt, and in August 2020 the replacement Casey Hut was opened.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/arthur-s-pass-national-park] This is a well known tramping trip that travels up the Mingha river to Goat Pass.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/arthur-s-pass-national-park] The second day involves travel down the Deception river and multiple river crossings.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/arthur-s-pass-national-park] It is possible to complete a side trip to Lake Mavis from Goat Pass.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/arthur-s-pass-national-park] This trip is used as the mountain run for the Coast to Coast race in the reverse direction.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/arthur-s-pass-national-park] Pest control (trapping stoats, weasels, rats and feral cats) occurs along this route as part of the Blue Duck Recovery Programme.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/arthur-s-pass-national-park] The Carroll Hut Track is on the West Coast side of Arthur′s Pass National Park, 3 kilometres north of Otira on State Highway 73 at Kellys Creek.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/arthur-s-pass-national-park] The tramp to the hut takes around three hours.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/arthur-s-pass-national-park] It is a steep climb through podocarp and broadleaf forest, providing good views of the Taramakau River on a clear day.
[src:arthur-s-pass-national-park/arthur-s-pass-national-park] The trip back from the hut to the road takes 90 minutes.
